sec.p:
To assess the potential application of the antioxidant flavonoids naringin and neohesperidin in the cosmetic industry, their skin permeability was evaluated using the in silico COSMOperm method, as previously described in the literature [30,31]. This model simulates the outermost layer of the skin, the epidermis, considering its differentiation into distinct compartments or layers, each with specific structural characteristics. Such an approach provides a detailed estimation of the dermal permeability of the evaluated compounds, offering insights into their potential topical bioavailability:
stratum corneum (“SC”; outer horny layer);
stratum granulosum (“SG”; granular layer, the outermost viable layer);
stratum spinosum (“SS”; viable prickle layer, releasing neutral barrier lipids);
stratum basale (“SB”; basal layer, metabolically active;
appendageal compartment (“shunt”; through the shunts provided by the hair follicles, sweat glands, and sebaceous glands).
